{"source_key":"sha256-c8597aca71664a84bdd657ea13dadbd3","record_index":1157,"record_hash":"sha256:60e3c94420f64e9acb80973b2dcd734d492f905ed76e811ae15e6fe7d092620a","timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:23:09.839Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n1. **The model says “turn,” but stores “capture batch.”**  \\n   That’s honest internally, but product use cases need conversation turns: prompt, response, tool calls, planning. A first backfill as one giant turn is basically useless for review sharing and mediocre for handoff.  \\n   **Doc change:** rename storage concept to `CaptureTurn` everywhere, and define a separate read/display grouping: `ConversationTurn` or `ProviderTurn`, derived from record metadata when possible.\\n\\n2. **Backfill is under-modeled for both use cases.**  \\n   “One backfill turn containing all records” preserves history but destroys reviewability. Review sharing needs to point at relevant prompts/responses inside that backlog.  \\n   **Doc change:** require record-level grouping fields sufficient to render logical turns even during backfill: provider turn key if available, plus fallback grouping by user message boundaries.\\n\\n3. **Environment-only observations are dismissed too aggressively.**  \\n   The doc says no turn unless new transcript records, but review evidence often happens between captures: user commits, rebases, pushes, changes branch state. You don’t need telemetry spam, but you do need interval evidence.  \\n   **Doc change:** keep no transcriptless turns for v1, but explicitly define how read-time scoring handles “latest turn snapshot vs current target state,” and call out that historical commit events between turns are lossy.\\n\\n4. **Review sharing privacy/export semantics are punted too late.**  \\n   The model stores prompts, responses, tool calls, paths, branch names, review ids, and changed files. That is fine inside repo metadata; it is not fine to expose automatically in a web review without a redaction/export contract.  \\n   **Doc change:** add a v1 non-goal or requirement: review sharing must go through an explicit projection that can redact records, tool payloads, paths, env details, and raw provider ids.\\n\\n5. **`observed_targets` duplicates snapshot data but lacks a strict invariant.**  \\n   If it is used for verification and rebuilds, it cannot be “compact vibes.” Readers need to know whether it is authoritative, derived, and exactly how it maps to `environment`.  \\n   **Doc change:** state: `observed_targets` is a deterministic projection of `environment`; readers may verify index hits against it; writers must derive it from the same snapshot in the same transaction.\\n\\n6. **Branch identity is still too vague.**  \\n   “Normalized full refname when available” is not enough in GitButler land, where virtual branches, stack branches, local refs, remote refs, and rewritten branches can drift. Branch-name evidence is weak, but the key still needs to be stable.  \\n   **Doc change:** define branch key precedence concretely: GitButler branch/change id when available, else full refname, plus display name separately. Say how virtual/unborn/unapplied branches key.\\n\\n7. **The scoring section is over-specified for v1 implementation and under-specified for product behavior.**  \\n   Lots of heuristic prose, but no crisp contract for what `findRelatedSessions(target)` must return.  \\n   **Doc change:** collapse weights discussion into a small contract: inputs, candidate indexes used, required reason kinds, confidence buckets, and “never claim authorship.”\\n\\n8. **Turn identity needs exact serialization rules.**  \\n   The hash recipe is close, but implementation will otherwise invent details: hash prefix inclusion, byte encoding, record hash formatting, array joining, empty handling.  \\n   **Doc change:** specify canonical bytes exactly, e.g. UTF-8 raw key strings, NUL separators, record hashes joined by NUL, no `sha256-` prefix inside digest unless explicitly included.\\n\\n9. **Record membership should require sequence, not just hashes/indexes.**  \\n   Handoff rendering needs stable ordering. Hash sets are not enough, and source indexes may be sparse or provider-specific.  \\n   **Doc change:** make `records` an ordered array and say order is authoritative for rendering within a capture turn.\\n\\n10. **The doc is doing too much.**  \\n   Storage model, association scoring, GitMeta atomicity, privacy, indexing, workspace APIs, and implementation checklist are all tangled. That makes the actual v1 contract harder to review.  \\n   **Doc change:** split into three sections with hard boundaries: persisted schema, derived indexes/read APIs, future scoring/product policy. Right now the model is solid-ish, but the spec shape invites accidental implementation of side quests.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T02:23:09.839Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}